# Auth & security

- Every non-public route depends on `current_user`. All mutating or consequential endpoints require an
  authenticated session; unauthenticated requests return 401.
- Credentials: argon2 password hashing or passkey/WebAuthn. Sessions are server-side via httpOnly,
  SameSite cookies with CSRF protection on mutating routes and sensible expiry/refresh.
- Approval and audit records reference the authenticated `user_id`. The human-approval gate and the
  assistant's stage-and-confirm both bind to that identity.
- Secrets (broker credentials, LLM provider API keys) live in a vault (AWS Secrets Manager; local dev `.env`).
  Broker credentials are injected ONLY into the execution scope — never the research agent, never the client.
  LLM keys never reach the browser. No secret may appear in any client-facing response (assert in tests).
- Scope every record by `user_id` even though Phase 1 is single-user, to keep the multi-user path open.
- Never log secrets or full credentials. Redact tokens in logs.
